{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508103"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.63,0.07,0.2,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42554"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the rural GP lead Emergency Department with new onset double vision, difficulty walking and dizziness. She noticed these symptoms two hours ago and also describes intermittent episodes of her heart racing over this time. She has a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia, hypertension, ischaemic heart disease (stable angina, nil previous MI\u0027s) and GORD. Her medications include aspirin, rosuvastatin, amlodipine and pantoprazole. She is an ex-smoker with a 30-pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOphthalmic examination shows ptosis, miosis and nystagmus of the right eye with reported diplopia. There is no inattention or field defects, or extraocular movement impairment. On the right side of the face there is decreased pain sensation compared to left. The gag reflex is also sluggish. Peripheral examination demonstrates 5/5 power in all limbs but decreased pain sensation on the left compared to right. When assessing gait, standing up she leans towards the right and cannot walk due to severe ataxia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following blood vessels is likely to be affected in the above clinical scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right MCA","Right PICA","Right SCA","Left PICA","Left AICA"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question requires correlation of all signs to make the diagnosis and knowledge of the corresponding vessel involved. The above is an example of a \u003Cem\u003Eright lateral medullary syndrome\u003C/em\u003E (Wallenberg syndrome), which would be explained by a \u003Cstrong\u003Eright PICA\u003C/strong\u003E occlusion (posterior inferior cerebellar artery).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis syndrome, and all brainstem syndromes, is best explained by the Rule of 4\u0027s which divides the brainstem anatomically into medial and lateral columns, as well as the 3 vertical regions of the brainstem (midbrain, pons and medulla). In lateral medullary syndrome, the lateral column is affected and at the level of the medulla which is supplied by the PICA. Involvement of the trigeminal nerve in the lateral column means there is ipsilateral sensory loss in the face and damage to the lateral spinothalamic tract (pain/temperature) means contralateral limb sensory loss due to decussation in the spinal cord. These cross findings are highly suggestive of a brainstem stroke/pathology. The other main finding is an ipsilateral (right sided in this case) Horner\u0027s syndrome, which results from impairment of the sympathetic nervous system fibers which run in the lateral brainstem column. There are several other symptoms present from involvement of other structures including impaired gag reflex (cranial nerve X), diplopia and dizziness (vestibular and cerebellar nuclei), gait ataxia (cerebellar impairment).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft PICA \u003C/strong\u003Eocclusion would manifest with the same symptoms as noted above for a right PICA stroke, but on the opposite side (e.g. left-sided Horner\u0027s syndrome, reduced pain sensation, left-leaning gait).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright MCA (middle cerebral artery) \u003C/strong\u003Eocclusion\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ewould cause left-sided hemiparesis (both upper and lower extremities and the lower half of the face); left-sided sensory loss of the left face, arm and leg; left-sided ataxia. If the patient is left brain-dominant, a right MCA stroke commonly results in left-sided spatial neglect. Less commonly, the patient\u0027s dominant hemisphere is right-sided, and a right MCA stroke will result in Broca\u0027s, Wernicke\u0027s or Global aphasia, depending on the region affected. This is unlikely, given the patient in the stem has reduced right-sided facial sensation (not left), and normal power in all limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight SCA (superior cerebellar artery) \u003C/strong\u003Estrokes\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Emay present with non-specific symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, dizziness and headache. Two patterns of symptoms can occur, depending on the location of the occlusion. A peripheral occlusion results in ipsilateral (right-sided) cerebellar signs (e.g. dysdiadokinesia, ataxia, nystagmus, intention tremor, slurred speech, hypotonia). An occlusion at the origin of the artery results in ipsilateral cerebellar signs, with Horner\u0027s syndrome and a contralateral sensory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral pontine syndrome, caused by occlusion of the AICA (anterior inferior cerebellar artery), is rare. However, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft AICA \u003C/strong\u003Estroke may present with vertigo, nausea and vomiting; left-sided hearing impairment, ipsilateral facial anaesthesia and paralysis; dysmetria, ataxia; and ipsilateral Horner\u0027s syndrome. While the presentation of these syndromes have considerable overlap, unlike PICA strokes, AICA strokes do not usually present with dysphagia, hoarseness and decreased gag reflex. Conversely, PICA strokes do not usually cause ipsilateral hearing impairment or ipsilateral facial paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When patients present with acute onset crossed sensory findings brainstem pathology such as lateral medullary syndrome must be considered."],"references":["Gates P. The rule of 4 of the brainstem: a simplified method for understanding brainstem anatomy and brainstem vascular syndromes for the non-neurologist. Intern Med J. 2005;35(4):263-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15836511/","Hong L, Cadogan M. Wallenberg Syndrome. In: Life in the Fast Lane [Online]. 2021; cited 2021 Aug 2. Available at: https://litfl.com/wallenberg-syndrome/.","Saleem F, Das JM. Lateral medullary syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551670/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90007"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T06:35:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T06:40:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2717"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only su